<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_MatrixScalarMultiplicationProperties"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>The scalar multiplication of a matrix by a number has the following properties</para.body>
      </para>
      <part.theorem partid="DistributesOverMatrixSum">
         <caption>Distributes over a matrix sum</caption>
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot (A + B) = t\cdot A\ +\ t\cdot B</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>matrix</term>
                  <term>scalar multiplication</term>
                  <term>distributes over matrix sums</term>
               </index.glossary>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>distributivity</term>
                  <term>scalar multiplication of matrices</term>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
      <part.theorem partid="ScalarSumDistributesOverMatrix">
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Scalar sum distributes over matrices: <math>
                     <latex>(s+t)\cdot A = s\cdot A + t\cdot A</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
      <part.theorem partid="ScalarsMultiplyAssociatively">
         <caption>Product of scalars multiplies associatively</caption>
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>(st)\cdot A = s\cdot (tA)</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>matrix</term>
                  <term>scalar multiplication</term>
                  <term>is associative</term>
               </index.glossary>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>associativity</term>
                  <term>scalar multiplication of matrices</term>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
      <part.theorem partid="MatricesMultiplyAssociatively">
         <caption>Product of matrices multiplies associatively into a scalar</caption>
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot (AB) = (tA)B</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
      <part.theorem partid="Commutativity">
         <caption>Left and right multiplication by a scalar are equal</caption>
         <part.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot A = A \cdot t</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>matrix</term>
                  <term>scalar multiplication</term>
                  <term>commutes with matrix multiplication</term>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
         </part.body>
      </part.theorem>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <para>
            <para.body>We verify the first distributivity property. The other two properties can be proved with the same method. So let <math>
                  <latex>A</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>B</latex>
               </math> be two matrices of size <math>
                  <latex>(m,n)</latex>
               </math>, and let <math>
                  <latex>t\in\RNr</latex>
               </math>. We focus our attention on the matrix entries in position <math>
                  <latex>(i,j)</latex>
               </math>, for some fixed <math>
                  <latex>1\leq i\leq m</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>1\leq j\leq n</latex>
               </math>. Suppose</para.body>
         </para>
         <ul>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>A</latex>
                     </math> has the number <math>
                        <latex>a_{ij}</latex>
                     </math> in position <math>
                        <latex>(i,j)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>B</latex>
                     </math> has the number <math>
                        <latex>b_{ij}</latex>
                     </math> in position <math>
                        <latex>(i,j)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
         </ul>
         <logic>
            <part.ref>DistributesOverMatrixSum</part.ref>
         </logic>
         <caption>
			Distributes over a matrix sum
		</caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>Let us consider the entry in position <math>
                  <latex>(i,j)</latex>
               </math> of the relevant matrix expressions:</para.body>
         </para>
         <ul>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>t\cdot (A+B)</latex>
                     </math> has the number <math>
                        <latex>t\cdot (a_{ij}+b_{ij})</latex>
                     </math> in position <math>
                        <latex>(i,j)</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
            <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>tA +tB</latex>
                     </math> has the number <math>
                        <latex>ta_{ij} + tb_{ij}</latex>
                     </math> in position <math>
                        <latex>(i,j)</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
         </ul>
         <para>
            <para.body>These numbers are equal because of the distributivity law for multiplication and addition of real numbers.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>Thus <math>
                  <latex>t(A+B)</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>tA+tB</latex>
               </math> both have the same number in position <math>
                  <latex>(i,j)</latex>
               </math>. This computation applies to each position. So the two matrices are equal and, therefore, the distributivity identity for scalar multiplication of matrices holds.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>You should try proving the remaining properties of scalar multiplication by adapting the above method.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
